    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters April 30 with a roster optimized to exploit speed-based volatility against specific pitching profiles. **Corbin Carroll** secures the highest daily efficiency score at 59.06, buoyed by a favorable matchup against Woodruff. While the SP skill remains a hurdle, the aggressive weighting toward SB potential\u2014given Woodruff\u2019s slow delivery\u2014elevates **Corbin Carroll** into our clear lead-off priority. Similarly, **James Wood** (55.45) warrants a start in the OF1 slot; despite the challenge posed by Peralta\u2019s elite 1.87s pop-time, **James Wood** benefits significantly from the leadoff spot and the stolen base upside inherent in the current matchup dynamic.\n\nThe lineup construction was anchored by calculated risks against tough left-handers, specifically with **Kyle Karros** (56.32). Although slotted 7th, his projection jumped significantly due to wind conditions and an favorable platoon edge against Abbott, narrowly outpacing the rest of the bench. **Mickey Moniak** was the most difficult exclusion of the morning. While he possesses a strong base projection of 56.28 and similar environmental advantages to **Kyle Karros**, he was ultimately benched due to a significant negative platoon adjustment (\u201315%) and lingering uncertainty regarding his presence in the starting lineup. \n\nStrategic caution is advised regarding **Austin Riley** (51.50) and **Brice Turang** (58.33). **Austin Riley** faces the formidable Valdez, F, whose elite skill suppresses his baseline; we are betting on his BvP and the secondary SB opportunities against a deliberate delivery. **Brice Turang** remains our steadiest play, providing the highest floor of the group. With **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Jose Caballero**, and **Josh Naylor** all idle today due to team off-days, our bench depth is severely restricted, forcing us to lean heavily on the remaining active roster to chase the efficiency gains derived from today\u2019s specific pitcher delivery speeds and park factors.",
